properties.name: Rara Lake
properties.description: Rara Lake, Nepal’s largest freshwater lake, sits at 2,990 meters in Mugu District, spanning 10.8 square kilometers with a depth of 167 meters. Surrounded by Rara National Park’s pristine forests and home to diverse flora and fauna, including the rare Rara snowtrout, its serene blue waters and stunning Himalayan backdrop make it a haven for nature lovers.

properties.name: Tilicho Lake
properties.description: Tilicho Lake, perched at 4,919 meters in Nepal’s Annapurna range, is one of the world’s highest alpine lakes, spanning 4.8 square kilometers with depths of 85 meters. Its turquoise waters, fed by glacial melt, are surrounded by stunning Himalayan peaks. Revered as the ancient Kak Bhusundi Lake in Hindu tradition, it offers trekkers breathtaking views and serene tranquility.

properties.name: Phewa Lake
properties.description: Phewa Lake, at 742 meters in Nepal’s Pokhara Valley, is a serene 5.7-square-kilometer gem reflecting the Annapurna range and Machhapuchhre peak. Home to the sacred Tal Barahi Temple and vibrant Lakeside area, it blends natural beauty and cultural charm, making it a must-visit destination.

properties.name: Gosainkunda Lake
properties.description: Gosaikunda Lake, at 4,380 meters in Nepal’s Langtang National Park, spans 13.8 hectares and reaches depths of 26.5 meters. Surrounded by rugged peaks, it is sacred in Hindu mythology as Lord Shiva’s abode. Each year, pilgrims flock here during Janai Purnima, drawn by its spiritual and serene beauty.

properties.name: Shey Phoksundo Lake
properties.description: Shey Phoksundo Lake, at 3,611.5 meters in Nepal’s Dolpa District, is the country’s deepest lake at 145 meters, spanning 4.94 square kilometers. Nestled in Shey Phoksundo National Park, it features turquoise waters, ancient stupas, and Nepal’s tallest waterfall. A haven for trekkers, it blends pristine beauty with cultural charm.

properties.name: Begnas Lake
properties.description: Begnas Lake, at 650 meters in Pokhara Valley, is Nepal’s third-largest lake, spanning 3.28 square kilometers with a depth of 10 meters. Surrounded by lush hills and stunning mountain views, it offers boating, fishing, and hiking, making it a serene retreat for nature lovers.

properties.name: Birendra Lake
properties.description: Birendra Lake, at 3,691 meters in Nepal’s Manaslu Glacier region, is a serene alpine gem formed by glacial melt. Surrounded by snow-capped peaks and lush forests, it offers breathtaking views and a tranquil retreat for trekkers on the Manaslu Circuit.

properties.name: Ghodaghodi Lake
properties.description: Ghodaghodi Lake, at 205 meters in Nepal’s Kailali District, spans 2,563 hectares with 13 interconnected lakes surrounded by tropical forests. A Ramsar site and bird sanctuary, it is home to 140+ bird species and holds cultural significance for the Tharu people, offering stunning biodiversity and natural beauty.

properties.name: Bis Hazari Lake
properties.description: Bis Hazari Lake in Chitwan’s buffer zone is a serene network of oxbow lakes, a haven for birdwatchers with species like white-rumped vultures and migratory Siberian birds. Its rich biodiversity and tranquility make it a must-visit for nature lovers.

properties.name: Rupa Lake
properties.description: Rupa Lake, at 600 meters in Kaski District, is Pokhara Valley’s third-largest freshwater lake, spanning 1.35 square kilometers. A haven for birdwatchers with 36 waterbird species, it offers boating, fishing, and serene natural beauty, making it a delightful escape for nature lovers.

properties.name: Khaptad Lake
properties.description: Khaptad Lake, at 3,050 meters in Doti District, is a serene freshwater lake within Khaptad National Park. A sacred site for Lord Shiva worship, it offers stunning views of the Api and Saipal ranges. With rich biodiversity and opportunities for trekking and birdwatching, it’s a peaceful retreat for nature lovers.

properties.name: Gangapurna Lake
properties.description: Gangapurna Lake, at 3,540 meters in Manang District, is a stunning glacial lake surrounded by the Annapurna range. A popular stop on the Annapurna Circuit, it offers serene views, though it is gradually becoming shallower due to glacier retreat.

properties.name: Gajedi Lake
properties.description: Gajedi Taal, or Danapur Lake, is a peaceful freshwater lake 21 kilometers west of Butwal, Nepal. Surrounded by lush greenery, it’s a popular spot for boating, picnics, and nature walks. A serene escape, it’s also close to Lausha Taal and Lumbini, the birthplace of Buddha.

properties.name: Kamal Pokhari Lake
properties.description: Kamal Pokhari, or “Lotus Pond,” is a historic site in Kathmandu, dating back to the Licchavi era and once used by the Malla kings. Recently restored, it remains a significant cultural landmark, though some conservationists have concerns over the use of concrete in its preservation.

properties.name: Bhairab Kunda Lake
properties.description: Bhairab Kunda, at 4,200 meters in Sindhupalchok, Nepal, is a sacred alpine lake dedicated to Lord Shiva. A key pilgrimage site, it offers a scenic trek through forests and meadows, with stunning Himalayan views and a chance to experience local Newar and Sherpa cultures.

properties.name: Gahana Pokhari Lake
properties.description: Gahana Pokhari, or “Jewel Pond,” in Hadigaun, Kathmandu, is a historic site known for the “Gahana Khojne Jatra” festival, where participants search for a lost jewel. It’s a popular cultural landmark, open year-round to locals and visitors.

properties.name: Nagdaha Lake
properties.description: Nagdaha, or “Snake Lake,” in Dhapakhel, Lalitpur, Nepal, is a serene 5-hectare lake surrounded by local legends. Home to diverse wildlife and over 50 bird species, it offers a peaceful spot for walks and relaxation, with ongoing efforts to improve water quality.

properties.name: Maidi Lake
properties.description: Maidi Lake, the smallest lake in Pokhara, Nepal, spans 1.17 hectares and offers a tranquil retreat. Despite contracting due to erosion, it remains a peaceful spot for visitors seeking serenity.

properties.name: Gupha Pokhari
properties.description: Gupha Pokhari, or Siddha Pokhari, is a sacred pond at 2,890 meters in Nepal’s Sankhuwasabha District. Revered by Hindus, Buddhists, and Kirat communities, it is fed by natural springs and features a small island. Known for its rich biodiversity, including 28 species of rhododendrons, it offers stunning views of Makalu, Kangchenjunga, and Everest on clear days.

properties.name: Khaste Lake
properties.description: Khaste Lake, located in Pokhara at 1,192 meters, spans 24.8 hectares and is known for its rich biodiversity. It’s a haven for migratory birds and supports pisciculture, benefiting the local economy. A peaceful spot for birdwatching and fishing, it’s a popular destination for nature lovers.

properties.name: Taudaha Lake
properties.description: Taudaha Lake, on the outskirts of Kathmandu, is a peaceful 500x400 meter freshwater lake. Known for its ecological importance as a stopover for migratory birds, it’s also steeped in local legends. A serene retreat, it’s a popular spot for nature lovers seeking tranquility.

properties.name: Jakhera Lake
properties.description: Jakhera Tal, in Dang District, Nepal, is a serene 3.7-hectare lake surrounded by lush forests. Known for its peaceful atmosphere and two temples, Ganesh and Siddeshwar Mahadev, it’s a popular spot for boating, fishing, and hiking.

properties.name: Tsho Rolpa Galcial Lake
properties.description: Tsho Rolpa, at 4,580 meters in Nepal’s Rolwaling Valley, is one of the largest glacial lakes in the country. Spanning 3.45 km in length and 0.5 km in width, it is surrounded by stunning peaks like Gaurishankar Himal. Despite concerns about potential GLOFs, it remains a popular trekking destination, offering breathtaking views and cultural experiences.

properties.name: Imja Tsho Lake
properties.description: Imja Tsho, located at 5,010 meters in Nepal’s Everest region, is a glacial lake formed by meltwater from the Imja and Lhotse Shar Glaciers. Spanning 1.3 km² and up to 90.5 meters deep, it has grown over time, raising concerns about GLOFs. Despite the risks, it’s a popular trekking spot, offering stunning views of Island Peak, Lhotse, and the Everest region’s beauty and culture.
